          <div class="content-section">
            <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">Overview</span><h2>What Are Tax Free Bonds?</h2></div>
            <p>Tax-free bonds are long-term debt instruments issued by government-backed Public Sector Undertakings (PSUs) like NHAI, REC, PFC, IRFC, and HUDCO. The key advantage is that interest income earned from these bonds is completely exempt from income tax under Section 10(15)(iv)(h) of the Income Tax Act, making them extremely attractive for investors in the 20% and 30% tax brackets.</p>
            <p>While the coupon rates on tax-free bonds (typically 5.5%–6.5%) may appear lower than regular bonds, their effective post-tax yield is significantly higher. For example, a tax-free bond offering 6% is equivalent to earning approximately 8.6% pre-tax for someone in the 30% tax bracket — far exceeding most bank FD returns after tax.</p>
            <p>Tax-free bonds were last issued through primary markets in 2015-16. However, they remain available on the secondary market (NSE/BSE) where they trade at premium or discount to face value. Given their scarcity and tax-exempt status, they are in strong demand among high-net-worth individuals and retirees seeking tax-efficient income.</p>
          </div>

