  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Tax Free Bonds</h2></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Are tax-free bonds still available for purchase?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Tax-free bonds are no longer issued through primary markets (last issued in FY 2015-16). However, you can purchase them on the secondary market through NSE and BSE. They trade under their respective ISIN codes and bond series. Given their scarcity and demand, they often trade at a premium to face value.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How is the post-tax yield of a tax-free bond calculated?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>To find the equivalent taxable yield: divide the tax-free coupon rate by (1 - your tax rate). For a 6% coupon in the 30% bracket: 6% ÷ (1 - 0.30) = 8.57%. This means you'd need an 8.57% return from a taxable instrument to match the 6% tax-free bond after tax. For the 20% bracket, the equivalent is 7.5%.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Are capital gains from tax-free bonds also tax-free?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>No, only the interest income is tax-free. If you sell tax-free bonds on the secondary market at a profit, capital gains tax applies. Short-term gains (held less than 12 months for listed bonds) are taxed at your slab rate. Long-term gains are taxed at 12.5% after indexation benefit. On maturity, you receive the face value — any premium paid is effectively a capital loss.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the risk of investing in tax-free bonds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Tax-free bonds have very low credit risk given their PSU/government backing and AAA ratings. The primary risk is interest rate risk — if rates rise, the market value drops (relevant only if selling before maturity). Liquidity risk exists as trading volumes can be thin on some days. There's also reinvestment risk since these bonds can't be replaced with new tax-free bond issues.</p></div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Should I buy tax-free bonds at a premium?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Buying at a premium reduces your yield-to-maturity since you'll receive only the face value at maturity. However, the tax-free coupon payments over the remaining tenure may still make it worthwhile. Calculate the YTM at the premium price and compare the post-tax equivalent with other available options. For investors in the 30% tax slab, the math often still favors tax-free bonds.</p></div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

